        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The molecular lines we plan to observe are CO (3-2) and 13CO (3-2), the most intense lines in typcial protoplanetary disks. The bandwidth is wider than the expected line width. To detect the velocity difference between eccentric and circular rotation, a velocity resolution better than ~0.05 km/s is required, so we adopt the setup having a velocity resolution of 0.03 km/s. We can smooth when we make images.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To measure the velocity difference between eccentric and circular orbital motions, an angular resolution of 0.2" is required to resolve disk motions outside the cavity whose radius is 0.2".
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To perform our analysis and to detect the disk eccentricity at a level &gt; 2sigma, S/N &gt; 5 is required for the emission originated from the region surrounding the cavity. We have constructed a
disk model of GM Aur based on observed density and temperature profiles, and estimated the CO (3-2) line intensity around the cavity is ~35 mJy per beam. Hence, we request a rms noise level of 7 mJy per beam to achieve S/N of 5 at a velocity resolution of 0.05 km/s.

The expected velocity difference between eccentric and circular orbital motions is ~0.2 km/s, so we aim to achieve a velocity resolution ~0.05 km/s.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
